Like the title says, support adding an `impl <type>` block anywhere and have it being handled correctly.

Like:

```rust
struct Foo;

pub fn main() {
    let value = {
        impl Foo {
            fn lol(self) {
                4
            }
        }
    };

    assert_eq!(Foo.lol(), 4);
}
```

This required the introduction of an intermediary step during indexing. We collect all impl blocks, and once the indexing queue is empty we start processing them. This ensures that imports are visible to the impl blocks and any other items (local or otherwise) which might affect the impl target. Luckily anything *inside* of the impl block itself can never be used as a target.

This avoids pre-checking `Value` by converting them into `Key` and (eventually) cloning the entire contents of a map when iterating over it.

This can only be merged once rust-lang/hashbrown#456 resolves and is released or an alternative solution is found.

This allows for any type which implements `HASH` and `EQ` to be used in a map. Including floats assuming they only normal or subnormal values that can be rectified:

```rust
use std::collections::HashMap;

pub fn main() {
    let map = HashMap::new();
    map.insert(1.0, 2.0);
    map.insert(0.0, 3.0);
    dbg!(map);
    dbg!(map[1.0]);
    dbg!(map.get(-0.0));
    dbg!(map[0.0]);
}
```

```
{1.0: 2.0, 0.0: 3.0}
2.0
Some(3.0)
3.0
```

This reworks how ranges are supported in Rune. Instead of modelling all ranges through a single `Range` type, we've reimplemented the full range of types internally:

* `RangeFrom` -  `start..`.
* `RangeFull` - `..`.
* `RangeInclusive` - `start..=end`.
* `RangeToInclusive` - `..=end`.
* `RangeTo` - `..end`.
* `Range` - `start..end`.

The benefits of doing this is significantly simplifying slice operations, better Rust correspondence, cheaper range construction (fewer instructions) and rejecting illegal range types at compile time.

All the new types have been documented, and error details have been improved, such as when trying to use an invalid iterator:

```rust
pub fn main() {
    for n in 1.0..2.0 {
        dbg!(n);
    }
}
```

This now gives detailed type information for the entire range:

```
error: internal vm error
  ┌─ .\scripts\test.rn:2:14
  │
2 │     for n in 1.0..2.0 {
  │              ^^^^^^^^ in this expression
  │
  = Cannot build an iterator out of f64..f64

Backtrace:
At .\scripts\test.rn:2:14:
    for n in 1.0..2.0 {
```

Finally we've also fixed parsing of `RangeFrom`, so that these loops are now correctly parsed:

```rust
pub fn main() {
    for n in 1.. {
        dbg!(n);
    }
}
```

Previously the `EagerBrace` parameter was not correctly propagating.

This is necessary to avoid unsound use of references in registered functions. An issue that was discovered when investigating #600.

The way function arguments are currently modeled uses unbound references, which among other things allow you to register a `'static` reference or any associated lifetime allowing values to escape:

```rust
#[rune::function]
fn download(url: &'static str) {
    todo!()
}

struct Foo<'a> {
    url: &'a str,
}

impl<'a> Foo<'a> {
    fn download(url: &'a str) {
        self.url = url;
    }
}

let module = Module::new();
module.function_meta(download);
```

With this change, functions like the above are correctly rejected instead. A downside is that we can no longer use references for arguments in async functions. Instead these must use owned types:

```rust
#[rune::function]
async fn download(url: &str) {
}
```
Becomes:
```rust
#[rune::function]
async fn download(url: Ref<str>) {
}
```
And associated types like this:
```rust
struct Foo;

impl Foo {
    #[rune::function]
    async fn download(&self, url: &str) {
    }
}
```
Becomes:
```rust
struct Foo;

impl Foo {
    #[rune::function(instance, path = Self::download)]
    async fn download(this: Ref<Self>, url: Ref<str>) {
    }
}
```

Allow one or more underscores at the start of a variable name, like so:
```rust
fn main() {
    let _a = 0;
    _a = 42;
    _a
}
```
This changes the lexer to allow underscores at the start of an identifier, and only emits `ask::Kind::Underscore` if it's strictly `_`.

Interestingly, [this seems to match the behavior in Rust](https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=stable&mode=debug&edition=2021&gist=c1e565a5f473afbf4f1ff4472177a9ac). They both treat more than one underscore as a valid identifier. So this would work in both Rust and Rune:
```rust
fn main() {
    let ___ = 0;
    ___ = 42;
    ___
}
```
(Assuming you mark `___` as `mut` in Rust.)

Personally, I find this behavior odd. But maybe matching the Rust compiler behavior is best?

Fixes #435.

This pull request allows Rune scripts to construct Rust types with named fields, like so:
```rust
#[derive(Default, Debug, Any, PartialEq, Eq)]
#[rune(constructor)]
struct External {
    #[rune(get, set)]
    suite_name: String,
    #[rune(get, set)]
    room_number: usize,
}
```
```rust
pub fn main() {
  let external = External {
      suite_name: "Fowler",
      room_number: 1300,
  };

  external
}
```
I've tested this with structs and it works as expected. It should also work with enum variants that have named fields, though I haven't tested that yet.

It does this by creating a closure during the `Any` macro expansion, and installing that as a constructor function associated with the type:
```rust
|suite_name: String, room_number: usize| {
    External { suite_name, room_number }
}
```
By invoking the constructor function, the VM is placing the `External` type onto the stack as a `Value::Any`. This means you can successfully extract the typed object using the `FromValue` trait:
```rust
let output = vm.call(["main"], ())?;
let output: External = rune::from_value(output)?;
println!("{:?}", output);
```

Right now, this relies on the caller to assign the struct fields in the correct order. Otherwise the call to the closure fails due to mismatched types. There are probably a few ways to fix that, including making the closure take a single `Object` argument and extracting the fields from it.

This probably also doesn't work with nested structs or generics, at least for the moment.

Fixes #400.

Add preliminary support for building and loading byte-code into the Vm from raw bytes, instead of having instructions always being an array of `Vec<Inst>`.

This has the potential of greatly reducing the size of Rune programs, but it comes with a performance penalty because instructions have to be decoded as they're being executed.

By default, we're still using the old array-based instructions format.

See the difference in in-memory size for the following program:

```rust
use std::iter::range;

pub fn main() {
    let it = range(0, 1000);
    let tail = 77;

    'label:
    while true {
        let value = 10;

        for n in it {
            loop {
                let value2 = 20;
                break 'label;
            }

            tail = tail + 1;
        }

        tail = tail + 1;
    }

    tail
}
```

Byte-code version: `196 bytes`.
Instruction array: `2560 bytes`.

This adds support for specifying generic arguments to `#[rune::function]`, such as sort:

```rust
/// Sort a vector of integers.
#[rune::function(instance, path = sort::<i64>)]
fn sort_int(vec: &mut Vec) {
    vec.sort_by(|a, b| match (a, b) {
        (Value::Integer(a), Value::Integer(b)) => a.cmp(b),
        // NB: fall back to sorting by address.
        _ => (a as *const _ as usize).cmp(&(b as *const _ as usize)),
    });
}
```

This change introduces two major differences:

Entries in modules and contexts are ordered according to their insertion order. This means that:
* Errors generated from them will always be consistent, like for context errors where an item is ambiguous.
* Documentation generated will always list items in their declaration order.

The second large change is that the way generics are looked up has changed. Previously looking up a free generic method wouldn't fail until runtime. Now when possible it will fail at compile time instead. Note that generic functions can only be defined in native contexts.

Additional changes:

Deriving `Any` now requires that you specify the correct item the type belongs to. Its item must correspond to the module it's being installed in.

```rust
#[derive(Any)]
#[rune(item = ::process)]
struct Process {
    /* .. */
}

fn install() -> Result<rune::Module, rune::ContextError> {
    let mut module = rune::Module::with_crate("process");
    module.ty::<Process>()?;
    Ok(module)
}
```

Macros now take paths and identifiers instead of strings, so this:
* `#[rune(name = "Foo")]` is `#[rune(name = Foo)]`.
* `#[rune(install_with = "path::to::function")]` is `#[rune(name = path::to::function)]`.
* `#[rune(module = "rune2")]` is now `#[rune(module = rune2)]`.
